  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Showcase project PBF in Primary Education in Uganda Kamuli district</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Improved availability and accessibility of good quality inclusive primary education in selected sub-counties of Kamuli district of Uganda, and a stronger Education system at large, which supports the progressive realization of Universal Primary Education Coverage (SDG 4) in this geographical area.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Ugandan education system with a school year running from February through to December, starts with 7 years of primary school education with the legal age of school entry of six year. In 1997 the Ugandan government introduced the Universal Primary Education (UPE) program to improve enrollment and attainment in primary schools. It was initially realized to provide free education for four children per family, later it was opened to all children of all families. When the new UPE policy was executed, schools experienced a massive influx of pupils and the demand for learning materials, teachers, and infrastructure became a challenge to the education system. This resulted in consequences, including but not limited to a poor quality education, low pupil achievement, untrained teachers,  exceeding the UPE required pupil-teacher ratio of 1:40, improper infrastructures and classroom settings, with classes having often between 70 and 150 pupils and over-age children studying in schools.  

After Primary Education, pupils can enter either Lower Secondary Education (Ordinary level, 4 year to pass their O-level) in order to continue with Advanced Secondary Education (Advanced level, 2 years) or a Technical college (3 years) followed by a study at a technical institute or primary teacher training. 

For the few students, that successfully pass the Advanced-level, the possibility to go to tertiary education (state, private or religiously affiliated university) opens up</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The projected will be implemented in 50 Primary schools of Kamuli District reaching 32,000 (16,295 - Girls and 15,705 - Boys) pupils as dircet beneficiaries</narrative>
  </description>
